"Our new service tested off the charts â€” more than 5% of customers we surveyed said they would buy it," one reader at a not-for-profit organization emailed me. "We launched it. The results were disappointing." Remember, customers lie. Not maliciously, but they lie. The reader learned that lesson the hard way. For his next idea he wanted to run a transaction-oriented test, but struggled with how to design and execute one.  Transaction-based learning need not be overly complicated. Consider these four options: These "low resolution" tests aren't perfect, but they are better than simply asking a customer, "Do you want this?" Remember, discount what customers say. Pay very careful attention to what they  do .